schelli nimz
1/11/2012 6:32:11 AM

                                    Faith- You are correct, there is no such thing as black henna. The powders and dyes sold as black henna usually have some nasty toxic chemicals in them. There is also no "clear" henna. Henna is red and that's it! You can modify the color with other herbs and extracts. To get a true black hair dye, you do a base layer of henna, and then another dye session using indigo. It gives a very nice natural black. I have to disagree with the author on henna. I have been using it since I was a teenager (I am 40 now). I have a lot of gray in my hair and henna covers it beautifully. Henna is brassy the first couple of days after dyeing, but it oxidizes to a more muted and natural shade very quickly. Henna also applies better as an "acid" dye. Human hair is like wool and other protien fibers. I mix mine with straight lemon juice and a little bit of coconut oil for extra conditioning. There is no need to heat anything, just let it sit covered for about 8 hours to get the best dye release. You can modify henna by making a strong tea of rose hips, or mexican saffron (you still use the lemon juice as the main liquid though). Beet juice, cherries, and red wine have all produced nice results too. The longer you leave a henna dye on, the more intense the color. I put a plastic shopping bag over my hair and cover it all up with a bandana and sleep on it.  There are some great resources on the web, and tons of photos of the varying shades you can achieve with henna mixed with other natural ingredients!
                                



eoz
8/29/2011 11:58:26 PM

                                    Tips for walnut dying: After making the walnut "juice" (simmering, straining, etc), boil it down for another 30 minutes to thicken it. Add a tsp of corn starch (pre-dissolved in a tbsp of cold water).  You can then mix the (room temp / cold) dying liquid in with a blended avocado, or a whipped egg white, or honey and oil, or thick conditioner, or full fat mayo. This will make it WAY easier to apply (and it's so good for your hair) and it will give you a few seconds to wipe it off before your skin before it stains (pure liquid stains much more quickly). Use a squirt bottle to access the back of your head without drips.
Cover your head with a bag after and gently blow dry your head (don't melt the bag) - the heat will help the dying the process.

And while you can use just about any part of the walnut, the husks are the best. You can get these for free outside in the fall if you know where to look!  You'll want to use 5-10 walnut husks per dye application depending on the size of the husks, how finely you crush them and how much hair you have.  Freeze extra hulls for use during the rest of the year.

Don't forget to eat the walnuts! After hulling, let them dry for a month in an old onion bag and then crack with a hammer.
                                



